# Repository Guidelines

## Project Structure & Module Organization
- Root documents hold the study material and tracking artifacts.
- Key files:
  - `edital_completo.md`: full edital content.
  - `edital_verticalizado.txt`: verticalized checklist source (by topics).
  - `edital_verticalizado.xlsx`: generated checklist spreadsheet.
  - `README.md`: quick usage guide.
- Optional study logs follow the README suggestion, e.g. `notas.md` and `questoes.md`.

## Build, Test, and Development Commands
- No build or runtime steps are required; this is a document-centric repository.
- If you add scripts, document them in `README.md` with example commands.

## Coding Style & Naming Conventions
- Use plain, readable Markdown or text. Keep sections short and focused.
- Prefer clear titles and dates in `YYYY-MM-DD` when logging progress.
- Suggested naming examples: `notas.md`, `questoes.md`, `2025-02-10-revisao.md`.

## Testing Guidelines
- No automated tests are currently defined.
- If you introduce scripts, include a simple validation step and document how to run it.

## Commit & Pull Request Guidelines
- Git history is minimal (single initial commit), so there is no established convention.
- Use concise, imperative commit messages (e.g., `add study notes`).
- PRs should describe the change, include the affected files, and mention any new files
  created for study tracking.

## Security & Configuration Tips
- Avoid committing personal data or credentials.
- Local environments (e.g., `.venv`) should remain untracked.

# DOCX creation, editing, and analysis

## Overview

A user may ask you to create, edit, or analyze the contents of a .docx file. A .docx file is essentially a ZIP archive containing XML files and other resources that you can read or edit. You have different tools and workflows available for different tasks.

## Workflow Decision Tree

### Reading/Analyzing Content
Use "Text extraction" or "Raw XML access" sections below

### Creating New Document
Use "Creating a new Word document" workflow

### Editing Existing Document
- **Your own document + simple changes**
  Use "Basic OOXML editing" workflow

- **Someone else's document**
  Use **"Redlining workflow"** (recommended default)

- **Legal, academic, business, or government docs**
  Use **"Redlining workflow"** (required)

## Reading and analyzing content

### Text extraction
If you just need to read the text contents of a document, you should convert the document to markdown using pandoc. Pandoc provides excellent support for preserving document structure and can show tracked changes:

```bash
# Convert document to markdown with tracked changes
pandoc --track-changes=all path-to-file.docx -o output.md
# Options: --track-changes=accept/reject/all
```

### Raw XML access
You need raw XML access for: comments, complex formatting, document structure, embedded media, and metadata. For any of these features, you'll need to unpack a document and read its raw XML contents.

#### Unpacking a file
`python ooxml/scripts/unpack.py <office_file> <output_directory>`

#### Key file structures
* `word/document.xml` - Main document contents
* `word/comments.xml` - Comments referenced in document.xml
* `word/media/` - Embedded images and media files
* Tracked changes use `<w:ins>` (insertions) and `<w:del>` (deletions) tags

## Creating a new Word document

When creating a new Word document from scratch, use **docx-js**, which allows you to create Word documents using JavaScript/TypeScript.

### Workflow
1. **MANDATORY - READ ENTIRE FILE**: Read [`docx-js.md`](docx-js.md) (~500 lines) completely from start to finish. **NEVER set any range limits when reading this file.** Read the full file content for detailed syntax, critical formatting rules, and best practices before proceeding with document creation.
2. Create a JavaScript/TypeScript file using Document, Paragraph, TextRun components (You can assume all dependencies are installed, but if not, refer to the dependencies section below)
3. Export as .docx using Packer.toBuffer()

## Editing an existing Word document

When editing an existing Word document, use the **Document library** (a Python library for OOXML manipulation). The library automatically handles infrastructure setup and provides methods for document manipulation. For complex scenarios, you can access the underlying DOM directly through the library.

### Workflow

    node,

# Then add comment on the newly created elements
# new_nodes[0] is the <w:del>, new_nodes[1] is the <w:ins>
doc.add_comment(start=new_nodes[0], end=new_nodes[1], text="Changed old to new per requirements")

nodes = doc["word/document.xml"].revert_deletion(del_elem)  # Returns [del_elem, new_ins]

# Reject all deletions in a paragraph

nodes = doc["word/document.xml"].revert_deletion(para)  # Returns [para]

## Tracked Changes (Redlining)

**Use the Document class above for all tracked changes.** The patterns below are for reference when constructing replacement XML strings.

### Validation Rules
The validator checks that the document text matches the original after reverting Claude's changes. This means:
- **NEVER modify text inside another author's `<w:ins>` or `<w:del>` tags**
- **ALWAYS use nested deletions** to remove another author's insertions
- **Every edit must be properly tracked** with `<w:ins>` or `<w:del>` tags

### Tracked Change Patterns

**CRITICAL RULES**:
1. Never modify the content inside another author's tracked changes. Always use nested deletions.
2. **XML Structure**: Always place `<w:del>` and `<w:ins>` at paragraph level containing complete `<w:r>` elements. Never nest inside `<w:r>` elements - this creates invalid XML that breaks document processing.

**Text Insertion:**
```xml
<w:ins w:id="1" w:author="Claude" w:date="2025-07-30T23:05:00Z" w16du:dateUtc="2025-07-31T06:05:00Z">
  <w:r w:rsidR="00792858">
    <w:t>inserted text</w:t>
  </w:r>
</w:ins>
```

**Text Deletion:**
```xml
<w:del w:id="2" w:author="Claude" w:date="2025-07-30T23:05:00Z" w16du:dateUtc="2025-07-31T06:05:00Z">
  <w:r w:rsidDel="00792858">
    <w:delText>deleted text</w:delText>
  </w:r>
</w:del>
```

**Deleting Another Author's Insertion (MUST use nested structure):**
```xml
<!-- Nest deletion inside the original insertion -->
<w:ins w:author="Jane Smith" w:id="16">
  <w:del w:author="Claude" w:id="40">
    <w:r><w:delText>monthly</w:delText></w:r>
  </w:del>
</w:ins>
<w:ins w:author="Claude" w:id="41">
  <w:r><w:t>weekly</w:t></w:r>
</w:ins>
```

**Restoring Another Author's Deletion:**
```xml
<!-- Leave their deletion unchanged, add new insertion after it -->
<w:del w:author="Jane Smith" w:id="50">
  <w:r><w:delText>within 30 days</w:delText></w:r>
</w:del>
<w:ins w:author="Claude" w:id="51">
  <w:r><w:t>within 30 days</w:t></w:r>
</w:ins>
```

from pathlib import Path
import re
from PIL import Image, ImageDraw

DOC_PATH = Path('unpacked/word/document.xml')

CONTENT_TYPES = Path('unpacked/[Content_Types].xml')
HEADER_PATH = Path('unpacked/word/header1.xml')
HEADER_RELS_PATH = Path('unpacked/word/_rels/header1.xml.rels')
MEDIA_PATH = Path('unpacked/word/media/notes_lines.png')

text = DOC_PATH.read_text(encoding='utf-8')

pgsz = re.search(r'<w:pgSz[^>]*w:w="(\d+)"[^>]*w:h="(\d+)"', text)
pgmar = re.search(r'<w:pgMar[^>]*w:top="(\d+)"[^>]*w:right="(\d+)"[^>]*w:bottom="(\d+)"[^>]*w:left="(\d+)"[^>]*w:gutter="(\d+)"', text)
if not pgsz or not pgmar:
    raise SystemExit('pgSz or pgMar not found')

w_twips, h_twips = map(int, pgsz.groups())
top_twips, right_twips, bottom_twips, left_twips, gutter_twips = map(int, pgmar.groups())

# A4/letter size in points (twips/20)
width_pt = w_twips / 20.0
height_pt = h_twips / 20.0

# Convert twips to inches, then to pixels at 96 DPI
DPI = 96
width_px = round((w_twips / 1440.0) * DPI)
height_px = round((h_twips / 1440.0) * DPI)

left_px = round((left_twips / 1440.0) * DPI)
right_px = round((right_twips / 1440.0) * DPI)
top_px = round((top_twips / 1440.0) * DPI)
bottom_px = round((bottom_twips / 1440.0) * DPI)

# Create transparent image with right-margin lines
img = Image.new('RGBA', (width_px, height_px), (255, 255, 255, 0))
draw = ImageDraw.Draw(img)
line_color = (200, 200, 200, 255)

x_start = width_px - right_px
x_end = width_px - 1

# Vertical separator line
if x_start < x_end:
    draw.line([(x_start, top_px), (x_start, height_px - bottom_px)], fill=line_color, width=1)

# Horizontal lines in note area
line_spacing_px = round((0.7 / 2.54) * DPI)  # ~0.7cm
for y in range(top_px + line_spacing_px, height_px - bottom_px, line_spacing_px):
    draw.line([(x_start + 2, y), (x_end, y)], fill=line_color, width=1)

MEDIA_PATH.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
img.save(MEDIA_PATH)

header_xml += f'''       xmlns:r="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/officeDocument/2006/relationships"\n'''

header_xml += f'''  <w:p>\n'''
header_xml += f'''    <w:r>\n'''
header_xml += f'''      <w:pict>\n'''
header_xml += f'''        <v:shapetype id="_x0000_t75" coordsize="21600,21600" o:spt="75" o:preferrelative="t" path="m@4@5l@4@11@9@11@9@5xe" filled="f" stroked="f">\n'''

header_xml += f'''            <v:f eqn="if lineDrawn pixelLineWidth 0"/>\n'''
header_xml += f'''            <v:f eqn="sum @0 1 0"/>\n'''
header_xml += f'''            <v:f eqn="sum 0 0 @1"/>\n'''

header_xml += f'''            <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelHeight"/>\n'''

header_xml += f'''          <o:lock v:ext="edit" aspectratio="t"/>\n'''
header_xml += f'''        </v:shapetype>\n'''
header_xml += f'''        <v:shape id="notesbg" type="#_x0000_t75"\n'''
header_xml += f'''          style="position:absolute;left:0;top:0;width:{width_pt:.2f}pt;height:{height_pt:.2f}pt;z-index:-251658240;mso-wrap-edited:f;mso-position-horizontal-relative:page;mso-position-vertical-relative:page"\n'''
header_xml += f'''          o:allowincell="f" o:allowoverlap="t">\n'''
header_xml += f'''          <v:imagedata r:id="rId1" o:title=""/>\n'''
header_xml += f'''          <w10:wrap type="none"/>\n'''
header_xml += f'''        </v:shape>\n'''
header_xml += f'''      </w:pict>\n'''
header_xml += f'''    </w:r>\n'''
header_xml += f'''  </w:p>\n'''
header_xml += f'''</w:hdr>\n'''

# Header relationships
header_rels = '''<?xml version="1.0" encoding="ascii"?>\n'''
header_rels += '<Relationships xmlns="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/package/2006/relationships">\n'
header_rels += '  <Relationship Id="rId1" Type="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/officeDocument/2006/relationships/image" Target="media/notes_lines.png"/>\n'
header_rels += '</Relationships>\n'

ids = [int(m.group(1)) for m in re.finditer(r'Id="rId(\d+)"', rels_text)]
new_id = max(ids) + 1 if ids else 1

    CONTENT_TYPES.write_text(ct_text, encoding='utf-8')

print(f'Added header relationship rId{new_id}')
